WEBVTT

00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:14.700
The layout of the glider chart.

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:19.720
As I said, when you glance at it once, you immediately want to close the chart again.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:21.740
There's almost a bit of a feeling of fear.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.500
At least with me that's how it was at the beginning, when I first sat down with it.

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:31.440
But once you look at the structure from the ground up and pick out each of these boxes

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:38.760
and then put them back into the chart, it's no longer quite so insanely complicated.

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:42.960
Then you know in principle what each box and each line means.

00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:46.160
And afterwards it's simply a huge number of them stacked on top of each other.

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:50.920
And sometimes it's still difficult to figure out which line belongs to which airspace.

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:54.040
But that's more of a visual problem.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:59.520
So I'd like to try to walk you through the understanding of the chart a little bit here,

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:02.120
and build up the chart from the ground up.

00:01:08.040 --> 00:01:13.320
So, as the first prominent line, there's the dividing line between the Mittelland and the Jura.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:14.640
And the Alps.

00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:18.020
It actually runs right across Switzerland, as you can see here.

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:22.860
Roughly at Lake Geneva, around Montreux, it cuts across through central Switzerland

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:29.280
to us in the Alpstein region and then on towards Austria.

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:31.920
And that's how Switzerland is divided.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:34.420
And this simply has a topographic background:

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:39.360
in the Jura and the Mittelland all the mountains are of course much lower,

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:41.220
and in the Alps they're a bit higher.

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:43.220
And so the airspaces are a little...

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:45.320
have been pushed much higher up.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:49.320
And that of course also has an impact on us as paraglider pilots.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.040
We'll get to that right now.

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:56.040
As I said, G and E we can fly in at any time.

00:01:56.040 --> 00:01:59.040
For C and D we need a clearance.

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:02.470
And for now you can simply picture G —

00:02:02.470 --> 00:02:06.470
the blue bar — as a carpet that's laid over the whole of Switzerland,

00:02:06.470 --> 00:02:08.470
over the entire topographic map.

00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:11.550
And the carpet is 600 metres thick.

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:13.950
And the transition...

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.080
Then, above those 600 metres,

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:20.090
you cross over into E.

00:02:20.090 --> 00:02:22.090
There we're still allowed to fly.

00:02:22.090 --> 00:02:26.200
It's just a different airspace with different rules.

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:30.200
For us as paraglider pilots we're allowed to fly into both.

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:32.200
After that it gets interesting for us:

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.200
namely, where is the boundary at which we cross over from E into C

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:38.200
and aren't allowed to fly any higher.

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:41.200
Where, even in super thermals, at some point we have to say,

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:44.200
okay, I'm in a thermal that would keep climbing,

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:46.200
cloud base is higher up,

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:48.200
but we have to leave this thermal and make sure

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.200
that we don't get into C.

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:53.200
And that's where it becomes exciting and also very important

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.200
that we know where this boundary is.

00:02:55.200 --> 00:03:00.440
In the Jura, as you can see, that is everything to the left of this cross-section,

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:03.440
this boundary sits at 3050 metres.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:07.900
In the Alps the boundary is at 4550 metres.

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:11.900
So you can see, we already have quite a difference in height here

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:14.900
and of course also in the possibilities we have with the paraglider.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:18.900
It's also very important to know — let's assume

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:21.900
this mountain here were 4200 metres high,

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:25.900
then we're still allowed 600 metres above it.

00:03:25.900 --> 00:03:30.900
So in that case you could fly up to 4800 metres

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:34.900
and clearly above those 4550 metres.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:38.900
The condition is simply that you never have more than 600 metres of ground clearance.

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:40.900
That's very important.

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:47.000
Now we've talked about these 4550 metres.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
It's very important to know

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
that this only applies when the military is not active,

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
when the military isn't in the air and isn't training.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And when the military is out flying,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.600
you see 'MIL ON' at the top left,

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:04.960
then something happens with this boundary:

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:08.980
it comes down to 3950 metres.

00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:11.980
Below that you can see the military hours shown,

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:13.980
which are also printed on the glider chart

00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:15.980
and very important to respect.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:17.980
So it's always Monday to Friday,

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:19.980
from 07:35 to 12:05

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:22.980
and from 13:15 to 17:05.

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:26.980
Those five minutes of buffer are simply to exclude overlap,

00:04:26.980 --> 00:04:31.670
so there are no collisions or incidents.

00:04:31.670 --> 00:04:34.670
So very important: when the military is active,

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:37.670
this boundary in the Alps comes down a bit,

00:04:37.670 --> 00:04:41.670
but is still clearly higher than in the Jura and the Mittelland.

00:04:41.670 --> 00:04:43.670
So a quick recap here.

00:04:43.670 --> 00:04:46.940
The transition from E to C happens in the Mittelland

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:49.940
at 3050.

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:54.940
In the Alps it varies depending on whether the military is active.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:05:02.110
There's a small point I forgot here

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:04.110
with all these airspaces.

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:06.110
Airspace D, which is also controlled

00:05:06.110 --> 00:05:10.110
and where we also need clearance even without radio contact,

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:14.110
applies above all in the vicinity of airfields.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:16.110
So we have G, the carpet laid over everything,

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:19.110
above that comes E and above that C,

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:21.110
and D comes in mainly over airfields.

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:23.110
Into play.

00:05:23.110 --> 00:05:29.160
Then all these airspaces are marked with what are called tags.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:32.160
You see them here on the left in theory

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.160
and on the right how they look on the chart.

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:39.160
And these tags always have a lower limit and an upper limit.

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:44.880
There it's very important that you see the difference

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:47.880
between upright numbers and italic numbers.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:49.880
If it's upright, it's above ground;

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:51.880
if it's written in italics, it's above sea level.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.880
And the second big difference you see here with these numbers

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:58.880
is that the upper number is highlighted in blue.

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:01.880
A number with a blue background means

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:06.950
that this is the altitude according to the standard atmosphere.

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:11.950
Now you see how, in paragliding or paraglider theory,

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:14.950
all these topics are always somewhat related

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:16.950
and dovetail into each other somewhere.

00:06:16.950 --> 00:06:19.950
In meteorology you've already heard a lot about the standard atmosphere.

00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:22.950
Here it's again about exactly the same thing —

00:06:22.950 --> 00:06:25.950
that the standard pressure is assumed.

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:31.950
So the number written in white is the actual, true altitude:

00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:34.950
if you look at the GPS reading

00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:38.950
or at a sign on a summit with the altitude on it,

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:41.950
i.e. really the actual hard edge.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.960
The blue-shaded number is then the figure

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:47.960
that can also fluctuate depending on the weather,

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:52.960
because you simply calculate the pressure reading back to sea level

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:54.960
and always assume

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:56.960
that at sea level the pressure is the same,

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:00.960
namely 1013.25 hectopascals.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:03.460
And why that's the case,

00:07:03.460 --> 00:07:06.460
I'll try to bring a bit closer to you

00:07:06.460 --> 00:07:08.460
in the next few slides.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:15.370
We measure altitude based on a pressure measurement.

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:18.870
That means your instrument measures

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:20.870
a certain pressure,

00:07:20.870 --> 00:07:23.870
unless of course we have an altitude reading from GPS,

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:26.870
but a standard altimeter,

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:28.920
which measures the pressure,

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:31.920
assigns a certain pressure to a certain altitude.

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:34.920
But this pressure fluctuates every day.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:36.920
On a mountain summit,

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:38.920
on the Säntis for example,

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:40.920
the pressure is not the same every day —

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:42.920
it varies daily.

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:44.920
And so you would actually have to

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:47.920
calibrate such an altimeter before every launch,

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:49.920
set it to launch altitude,

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:51.920
so that it is correct on that day.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:52.920
But it's also the case

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:56.920
that over the course of the day the pressure can shift a bit,

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:58.920
and then in the evening after landing

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:06.550
the altimeter can already be off by a few metres again.

00:08:06.550 --> 00:08:10.270
And for that a solution has been found.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:13.270
And this solution is called flight levels —

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:15.270
Flugflächen.

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:18.270
And it comes from international aviation.

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:19.270
Because aircraft

00:08:19.270 --> 00:08:21.270
that fly from one place to another

00:08:21.270 --> 00:08:24.270
over greater distances

00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:26.270
also pass through different weather zones

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:29.270
and different pressure systems.

00:08:29.270 --> 00:08:30.270
And that would mean

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.270
that you would essentially have to

00:08:32.270 --> 00:08:37.410
recalibrate the altimeter every few metres or every few kilometres

00:08:37.410 --> 00:08:39.410
of flight,

00:08:39.410 --> 00:08:41.410
would have to reset it to the local ground pressure.

00:08:41.410 --> 00:08:43.410
You'd somehow have to keep radioing in,

00:08:43.410 --> 00:08:44.410
what's the weather here,

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:45.410
what's the ground pressure here,

00:08:45.410 --> 00:08:46.410
so that this altitude is correct.

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:48.410
And that would of course be almost impossible

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:50.410
and extremely tedious.

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:52.410
And it would also carry the risk

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:55.410
of perhaps immediately making a calculation error,

00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:57.410
or that the pressure swing changes at exactly the wrong moment,

00:08:57.410 --> 00:09:01.520
and that there would then be collisions.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:04.880
And so in aviation people agreed

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:09.880
that you don't fly by actual altitudes,

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:12.480
but by standard pressure.

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:14.480
Standard pressure, as I said,

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:18.480
is 1013.25 hectopascals at sea level.

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:21.480
And now I have a quick little calculation example

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:25.490
before we go back to the flight levels

00:09:25.490 --> 00:09:28.490
and how it works in practice.

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:30.490
Just so that you can picture a little

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:31.490
what that means.

00:09:31.490 --> 00:09:35.470
So the example with Flight Level 100.

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:38.470
One flight level is 100 feet.

00:09:38.470 --> 00:09:42.470
That means Flight Level 100 is 10,000 feet.

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:46.470
And because one foot is 30.48 cm,

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:50.470
Flight Level 100 is then 3,048 metres.

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:53.470
And so we see the connection again,

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:55.470
or we can explain to ourselves

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.470
why, for example, in the Jura

00:09:57.470 --> 00:10:03.470
airspace C starts at 3,050 metres.

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:05.470
That is namely Flight Level 100,

00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:08.470
and comes from airline aviation.

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.470
And it's exactly the same in the Alps.

00:10:10.470 --> 00:10:13.470
The 3,950 are Flight Level 130,

00:10:13.470 --> 00:10:21.640
and the 4,550 are Flight Level 150.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:23.640
And at lower altitudes it's of course important

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:27.110
that an aircraft can fly to exact altitudes.

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:29.110
Simply because of the topography,

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:32.110
so that there are no collisions with mountains

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:33.110
or with obstacles.

00:10:33.110 --> 00:10:37.110
But at a certain altitude it really doesn't matter so much any more

00:10:37.110 --> 00:10:40.110
whether the aircraft cross paths up here

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:44.110
or cross paths a little lower down.

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:45.110
The most important thing is simply

00:10:45.110 --> 00:10:47.110
that the aircraft are separated

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:49.110
and don't fly at the same altitude.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:51.110
And that is precisely what was introduced

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:53.110
with the flight level.

00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:56.110
Because you can see, when an aircraft

00:10:56.110 --> 00:10:59.110
flies from a high into a low,

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:01.110
the curve doesn't have to be this extreme of course —

00:11:01.110 --> 00:11:03.110
this is a bit exaggerated for illustration —

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:06.110
but then the flight level fluctuates a little.

00:11:06.110 --> 00:11:09.110
So the aircraft drifts a bit,

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:11.110
goes a little higher, a little lower.

00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:13.110
But it is always on the same pressure —

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:15.110
it flies on exactly the same pressure surface.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:17.640
And then it really doesn't matter

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.640
whether it's at 11,000 or at 10,900.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:22.640
What's important is that the aircraft fly at different levels.

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:26.640
And that they can avoid a collision that way.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:29.900
Application in the glider charts

00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:36.090
appears above all with TMAs and with airways.

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:38.240
We'll come back to those later,

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:39.240
and how they're structured.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:42.240
But simply, if you look at the tags here again,

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:44.240
with the D, airspace D,

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:46.240
they always have a lower edge.

00:11:46.240 --> 00:11:48.240
Here it's ground.

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:51.240
Here we also have a lower edge of 2,250 and 2,600.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:53.240
And that is fixed.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:54.240
It's really important here

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:56.240
that it's fixed, because of the topography.

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:58.240
This is the example of Meiringen here,

00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:01.240
where there are very high mountains on the left and right.

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:03.960
The upper limit, the 3,950,

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:05.960
there we're back in the range

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:07.960
where it doesn't matter at all,

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.960
because there are no more obstacles.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:13.310
That altitude can then fluctuate.

00:12:13.310 --> 00:12:17.310
And that's explained a bit more on this slide.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:20.310
So you can see, we have a piece of topography here.

00:12:20.310 --> 00:12:22.310
This lower edge is very sharp,

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:24.310
because if this here were to fluctuate based on pressure,

00:12:24.310 --> 00:12:26.310
then we'd have a problem here.

00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:28.310
Then suddenly a TMA,

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:29.310
an approach corridor,

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:33.520
would run right into mountain terrain

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:36.630
and could cause a collision.

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:38.630
The upper edge, however, does fluctuate.

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:41.800
And how much that amounts to,

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:42.800
you can see here.

00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:43.800
It's also interesting

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:45.800
to know for when we're paragliding.

00:12:45.800 --> 00:12:48.910
By the way, this is also printed on the glider chart,

00:12:48.910 --> 00:12:49.910
these numbers.

00:12:49.910 --> 00:12:50.910
So you can see,

00:12:50.910 --> 00:12:53.910
at 1,037 hectopascals

00:12:53.910 --> 00:12:54.910
ground pressure.

00:12:54.910 --> 00:12:55.910
And that is, well,

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:58.080
calculated back as the ground pressure,

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:00.080
that's of course already very high —

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:02.080
a strong high.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:05.290
And there it amounts to about 200 metres.

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:08.400
Conversely, in a very deep low-pressure area

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:10.400
it makes for minus 200 metres.

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.400
So that's already quite a lot.

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:15.090
What you can also say:

00:13:15.090 --> 00:13:18.560
in such a deep low we're probably not flying,

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:19.560
as a rule,

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:21.560
because it's simply really bad weather

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:23.560
and a storm is forecast.

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:25.560
In an extremely strong high we are,

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:27.560
we might do a glide-only flight

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:29.560
from a high-Alpine peak,

00:13:29.560 --> 00:13:31.560
but probably also less of a thermal flight,

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:33.560
because it's just too stable again.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:35.560
Now we're again drifting a bit

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:36.560
into meteorology.

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:39.560
But most of the time we're in the range

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:41.560
of perhaps plus,

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:43.560
perhaps even 100 metres,

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:45.560
in the air doing a thermal flight.

00:13:45.560 --> 00:13:46.560
And the good thing is then

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:49.560
that these boundaries above all tend to move upwards.

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:50.560
So if you know,

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:51.560
above is an airspace

00:13:51.560 --> 00:13:53.560
that starts at 3,050

00:13:53.560 --> 00:13:54.560
and you're on a thermal flight,

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:56.570
then it's mostly the case

00:13:56.570 --> 00:13:59.570
that the boundary is a bit higher.

00:13:59.570 --> 00:14:01.570
But that's of course exactly why it's important

00:14:01.570 --> 00:14:03.570
that the instrument is set correctly

00:14:03.570 --> 00:14:05.570
and that we don't fly into it.

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:10.900
After that, for a change, an exam-style question

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:13.560
that could come up for you

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:15.560
at the paragliding theory exam.

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:16.560
You can see here:

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:19.560
the upper limit of airspace class E

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:21.560
over the Jura is asked for.

00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:23.560
Then you have to first think about,

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:26.560
well, how high would it be normally?

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:28.560
Jura, as we said,

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.640
regardless of whether military is active or inactive,

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:34.640
the upper limit for us is at 3,050.

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:36.640
Now we have a very strong high.

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:39.640
At first glance you see lots of numbers

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:40.640
and immediately get the feeling,

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:43.640
oh wow, what exactly do I have to calculate now and so on.

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:44.640
But actually,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:45.640
you're not required

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:47.640
to perform calculations.

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:48.640
You just have to see,

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:51.640
hey, this is an insanely strong high.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:53.640
With a very strong high,

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:55.640
it makes at most about 200 metres.

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:57.640
And here you quickly see:

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:00.640
3,900 or 4,100 would of course be far, far too much.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.640
It doesn't shift by that much.

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:06.640
It moves within a range of plus or minus 200 metres,

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:11.200
if such an exam question comes up for you.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:14.240
Now we've made a small detour

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:16.240
in the direction of Flight Level.

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:20.240
Slightly off-topic from the glider chart,

00:15:20.240 --> 00:15:22.240
but I think it was necessary

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:23.240
for the understanding

00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:25.240
of how the airspaces are structured.

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:26.240
I hope

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:28.240
it has helped you a little.

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:29.240
Now we'll come back

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:31.240
to the other airspaces.

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:33.240
Here is now airspace D,

00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:35.240
which I briefly touched on earlier.

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:37.240
Those are the CTRs,

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:38.240
the control zones,

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:40.240
which sit in the immediate vicinity

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:42.240
of the major airports.

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:44.240
And they always go from the ground

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:46.320
up to a certain altitude.

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.320
The altitude and also the shape

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:50.320
are of course highly dependent on the topography

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:53.320
and also on the approach corridors

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.040
and on the needs of that airport.

00:15:56.040 --> 00:15:58.040
And they're of course not always round.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:16:00.040
This is just shown symbolically.

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:02.600
Above that come the TMAs,

00:16:02.600 --> 00:16:04.600
the terminal control areas.

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:05.600
You can again picture them

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:07.600
like boxes stacked on top of each other.

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:12.240
With TMAs there's something a bit special.

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:14.240
So here for example a CTR.

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:16.520
Then you have a TMA,

00:16:16.520 --> 00:16:19.520
where the box actually runs into a mountain

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:21.520
or into terrain.

00:16:21.520 --> 00:16:22.630
That happens sometimes.

00:16:22.630 --> 00:16:25.630
And here it's really important to know

00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:27.630
that with the paraglider

00:16:27.630 --> 00:16:30.680
— but caution, only south of the dividing line

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:32.680
Mittelland–Alps, so only in the Alps —

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:36.680
you'll fly out 300 metres below it.

00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:38.680
That happens in very few cases.

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:40.680
That's also an exam question

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:42.680
that's a bit tricky,

00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:44.680
where you might get caught.

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:46.680
Watch out with these 300 metres.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:49.430
Of course there are launch sites

00:16:49.430 --> 00:16:51.430
where for example you launch here

00:16:51.430 --> 00:16:53.430
and can wonderfully fly out below these 300 metres

00:16:53.430 --> 00:16:55.430
down here

00:16:55.430 --> 00:16:57.430
and are absolutely legal at all times.

00:16:58.430 --> 00:17:00.430
And don't need a clearance for it.

00:17:00.430 --> 00:17:04.170
Then we also have the airway.

00:17:04.170 --> 00:17:07.170
That then connects the larger airports

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:10.170
and also the main traffic axes

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:12.170
of international air traffic.

00:17:12.170 --> 00:17:15.540
Here once again a small side view.

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:19.540
You see, there can be multiple TMAs.

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:22.540
There can be five, six, seven TMAs.

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:23.540
There can be only one.

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:24.540
It really varies.

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:25.540
And as I said,

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:26.540
it depends entirely on the air traffic

00:17:26.540 --> 00:17:28.540
and on the topography of the airport.

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:30.160
The activity of these TMAs

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:35.160
and these CTRs can also vary.

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:36.760
If a 9 is shown,

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:40.760
so we have the designation CTR LSZR here,

00:17:40.760 --> 00:17:41.760
if a 9 is shown,

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:43.760
then it is permanently active,

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:46.760
as for example in Zurich at the major airports.

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:47.760
If it's HX,

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:50.760
then it has no fixed operating hours,

00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:53.760
but you basically have to assume

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:55.760
that it can be active at any time

00:17:55.760 --> 00:17:57.760
and that you can query the status.

00:17:57.760 --> 00:17:59.760
And then there are the temporary ones.

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:05.060
The temporary ones are then announced via the DABS,

00:18:05.060 --> 00:18:07.060
when they are active.

00:18:07.060 --> 00:18:09.060
In Switzerland there are only two cases:

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:10.060
Sion and Alpnach.

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:12.060
We'll come back to this example a bit later.

00:18:12.060 --> 00:18:20.020
Those are the three activity states of TMAs and CTRs.

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:25.210
In Switzerland we have a whole lot of heliports.

00:18:25.210 --> 00:18:27.210
They're marked like this.

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:30.320
And we have to keep a radius of two and a half kilometres

00:18:30.320 --> 00:18:33.140
from them.

00:18:33.140 --> 00:18:37.510
Smaller airfields without CTRs are marked like this.

00:18:37.510 --> 00:18:40.680
They have a radius of five kilometres

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:42.680
from which we have to keep our distance.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:44.760
Here we have another little summary.

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:45.760
Here in the Lucerne area,

00:18:45.760 --> 00:18:48.760
this is somewhat the Bermuda Triangle for us

00:18:48.760 --> 00:18:49.760
paraglider pilots,

00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:51.760
where we really have to watch carefully

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:53.760
not to enter anyone's airspace.

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:55.760
But a really beautiful flying area.

00:18:55.760 --> 00:18:57.760
And you can certainly fly there,

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:00.760
even if it looks very, very complex here.

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:02.760
On this picture you can see all the examples

00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:03.760
that exist.

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:06.760
So there's the heliport with two and a half kilometres,

00:19:06.760 --> 00:19:08.760
the civil airfield.

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:10.760
Then there are mixed airfields

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:12.760
that are used for military and civilian purposes.

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:14.760
And then there are purely military airfields,

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:18.060
which are circled in red.

00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:20.330
Also interesting:

00:19:20.330 --> 00:19:23.330
it only goes up to 600 metres above ground.

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:27.920
So you could fly more than 600 metres above it

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:33.560
without getting into trouble there.

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:35.560
On this topic it's also important:

00:19:35.560 --> 00:19:37.560
if you've planned a cross-country flight somewhere

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:38.560
and have the feeling,

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:41.930
this is where my ideal flight route and the thermals go,

00:19:41.930 --> 00:19:44.930
and the angle of the terrain and so on,

00:19:44.930 --> 00:19:47.930
and my route would actually go right through there

00:19:47.930 --> 00:19:51.930
or would just barely scrape the heliport,

00:19:51.930 --> 00:19:55.110
then it's definitely worth the time

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:57.110
to quickly follow up

00:19:57.110 --> 00:20:00.110
and check at the SHV under the local agreements

00:20:00.110 --> 00:20:02.110
whether perhaps for this heliport

00:20:02.110 --> 00:20:04.110
there is even a local arrangement.

00:20:04.110 --> 00:20:05.110
If you don't have any further info,

00:20:05.110 --> 00:20:07.110
you always have to assume

00:20:07.110 --> 00:20:09.110
it's a two-and-a-half-kilometre radius

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:11.110
and a five-kilometre radius at the airfields

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:13.110
and 600 metres.

00:20:13.110 --> 00:20:16.110
But perhaps it's like here at Trogen,

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.110
where a wedge has been cut out,

00:20:18.110 --> 00:20:20.110
where you can absolutely fly through the area.

00:20:20.110 --> 00:20:22.110
And in addition you see

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:25.110
that here it now says Ground to 1200 metres.

00:20:25.110 --> 00:20:28.220
Trogen, however, is about 800–900 metres.

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:32.220
That means it's clearly less than 600 metres as well.

00:20:32.220 --> 00:20:34.220
And that can help you a lot

00:20:34.220 --> 00:20:36.220
later in practice,

00:20:36.220 --> 00:20:41.440
if you have such additional information.

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:43.440
Then we also have obstacles

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:45.720
marked on the glider chart.

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:48.660
They look something like this.

00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:50.660
Here the Säntis example.

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:52.930
We have the obstacle.

00:20:52.930 --> 00:20:55.930
At the top it says it has a light.

00:20:55.930 --> 00:20:57.930
That's more important for aircraft

00:20:57.930 --> 00:20:59.930
that are out at night,

00:20:59.930 --> 00:21:00.930
to know that it's lit.

00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:02.930
For us, less interesting.

00:21:02.930 --> 00:21:03.930
What's also interesting for us

00:21:03.930 --> 00:21:04.930
is to see the height.

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:06.930
And here it comes into play

00:21:06.930 --> 00:21:08.930
with the italic font and the upright font.

00:21:08.930 --> 00:21:10.930
Italic means above sea level.

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:12.930
So that's the top of the antenna.

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:15.930
And the 124 metres, the upright font,

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:17.930
that's how tall the antenna actually is.

00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:18.930
So you know,

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:21.110
okay, the antenna is this big,

00:21:21.110 --> 00:21:23.110
I should be able to see it from far away.

00:21:23.110 --> 00:21:25.110
It just gives us a little reference point.

00:21:25.110 --> 00:21:27.110
Also important are the cables

00:21:27.110 --> 00:21:28.110
that are marked.

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:31.110
With these 100 and 264 metres

00:21:31.110 --> 00:21:34.110
it simply gives the maximum clearance above the ground.

00:21:34.110 --> 00:21:36.110
So here too you can estimate a bit

00:21:36.110 --> 00:21:38.800
how big these cables are.

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:39.800
Very important,

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:40.800
watch out,

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:41.800
not every obstacle

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:44.800
is shown on the glider chart.

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:45.800
There are many obstacles

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:47.800
that aren't in here.

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:49.800
For that you should also look at the aeronautical obstacle chart

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:51.800
as well.

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:53.800
And even when you've checked that,

00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:55.800
fly with your eyes open.

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:57.800
Don't just blindly fly into somewhere,

00:21:57.800 --> 00:21:59.800
because there can always be

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:02.800
a logging or hay cable strung up somewhere

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:05.840
that, by law, doesn't have to be charted.

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:10.840
And that can become your downfall.

00:22:10.840 --> 00:22:12.840
So always fly with your eyes open

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:14.840
and also talk to the locals.

00:22:14.840 --> 00:22:16.840
And at the clubs and associations

00:22:16.840 --> 00:22:18.840
and also at the valley stations of the cable cars

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:20.840
you'll usually find pretty good info

00:22:20.840 --> 00:22:22.840
on such aeronautical obstacles.

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:25.840
So on this topic don't rely a hundred per cent

00:22:25.840 --> 00:22:27.840
only on the glider chart.

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:33.390
You also see plenty of these.

00:22:33.390 --> 00:22:36.390
The LS-Rs, the red ones.

00:22:36.390 --> 00:22:37.760
The red Rs

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:39.760
are Restricted.

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:41.930
So we're not allowed to fly into those.

00:22:41.930 --> 00:22:43.930
On the glider chart

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:45.930
the ones that are very frequently active

00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:47.930
are marked.

00:22:47.930 --> 00:22:49.930
And then again we go into the DABS

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:51.930
the evening before, to check

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:53.930
whether it's also active on the day

00:22:53.930 --> 00:22:58.000
I want to fly or not.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
Then there's also the LS-D.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:01.000
That's not Restricted.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.010
That's Danger.

00:23:03.010 --> 00:23:06.410
There you can in principle fly in.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:08.410
It's just not recommended,

00:23:08.410 --> 00:23:09.410
because dangerous activities may be taking place.

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:11.410
Like shooting exercises, for example.

00:23:11.410 --> 00:23:13.410
On the ground below.

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:16.410
And then to fly straight into that airspace

00:23:16.410 --> 00:23:18.430
is of course not recommended.

00:23:18.430 --> 00:23:24.800
But in principle not legally forbidden.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:26.800
Here we have an example of such an LS-R

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:28.800
in our region.

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:30.800
Above the Alpstein and Lake Walen.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:32.800
LS-R 3.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:35.520
And here you can again see

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:37.520
the lower and upper limits.

00:23:37.520 --> 00:23:39.520
They're shown shaded in red here.

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:41.520
And that again means

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:43.520
that the whole atmosphere is red.

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:45.520
And that the whole box of the training area

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:47.520
of the military can fluctuate.

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:49.520
It can sometimes be a bit higher

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:54.000
or sometimes a bit lower.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
Here marked a bit better,

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:02.370
so you can see it clearly.

00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:04.370
A short explanation about the DABS.

00:24:04.370 --> 00:24:07.370
You'll find the DABS at www.skybriefing.com

00:24:07.370 --> 00:24:10.370
Right at the start, very important input.

00:24:10.370 --> 00:24:12.370
Always check that the date is correct.

00:24:12.370 --> 00:24:14.370
Because if you look at the wrong day

00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:16.370
and have the feeling

00:24:16.370 --> 00:24:18.370
that you can fly in everywhere,

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:20.370
and on the day you're actually out

00:24:20.370 --> 00:24:22.370
some shooting exercises are taking place,

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:24.370
that's of course very unfortunate.

00:24:24.370 --> 00:24:26.370
Always check that the date is correct.

00:24:26.370 --> 00:24:28.370
Here you can see on this map

00:24:28.370 --> 00:24:30.370
the LS-Rs marked in red

00:24:30.370 --> 00:24:32.370
are not widely spread.

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:34.370
There aren't very many active.

00:24:34.370 --> 00:24:38.370
The one over our Alpstein isn't active either.

00:24:38.370 --> 00:24:40.370
That doesn't mean they have to be active all the time,

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:42.370
just because they're on the glider chart.

00:24:42.370 --> 00:24:44.370
Those are simply the ones

00:24:44.370 --> 00:24:46.370
that are used very often.

00:24:46.370 --> 00:24:48.370
That's why they're permanently on the chart.

00:24:48.370 --> 00:24:50.370
But on the day itself you have to

00:24:50.370 --> 00:24:52.370
always quickly check the DABS.

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:54.370
I've taken the D12 as an example here.

00:24:54.370 --> 00:24:56.370
Near Einsiedeln.

00:24:56.370 --> 00:24:58.370
Here you have, of course,

00:24:58.370 --> 00:25:00.370
very little information about it.

00:25:00.370 --> 00:25:03.220
And down in the legend

00:25:03.220 --> 00:25:05.400
you can then see when

00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:07.860
and up to what altitude

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:09.910
this airspace is closed.

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:11.910
Or whether it's declared as a Danger Area

00:25:11.910 --> 00:25:13.910
instead.

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:15.910
And also what's going on down there.

00:25:15.910 --> 00:25:17.920
Here too I recommend,

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:19.920
just have a look from time to time.

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:21.920
Even if you maybe aren't going flying

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:23.920
and are stuck at the office that day.

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:25.920
Just have a quick look.

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:28.260
It's sometimes interesting what else you discover.

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:30.880
And here it's still

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:32.880
extremely important to watch the time.

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:34.880
It's in UTC.

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:36.880
UTC

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:39.000
is the standard time.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
In winter we have to add an hour

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
for Swiss time.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.000
And in summer add 2 hours,

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
to get the active time.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
So if it says here

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
it's active from 07:00,

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:53.000
then in summer it's only active from 09:00.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
Depending, that can be good for us.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.040
Or it can not work in our favour.

00:25:57.040 --> 00:25:59.040
And shorten our flight time a bit,

00:25:59.040 --> 00:26:01.040
the time we get to fly through there.

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:08.920
As chance would have it,

00:26:08.920 --> 00:26:10.920
on this,

00:26:10.920 --> 00:26:12.920
in this DABS,

00:26:12.920 --> 00:26:14.920
the temporary TMA of Sion was

00:26:14.920 --> 00:26:16.920
active.

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:18.920
You don't see that very often,

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:20.920
but it's perfect for showing

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:22.920
the three activity states

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:24.930
that a TMA

00:26:24.930 --> 00:26:26.930
or CTR can have.

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:28.930
Sion and Alpnach,

00:26:28.930 --> 00:26:30.930
as I said, are the only ones

00:26:30.930 --> 00:26:32.930
that are communicated via the DABS.

00:26:32.930 --> 00:26:34.930
And here you can see right now

00:26:34.930 --> 00:26:36.930
how it then looks.

00:26:36.930 --> 00:26:39.400
On the glider chart,

00:26:39.400 --> 00:26:41.400
it's a very subtle detail.

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:43.410
You can barely see it,

00:26:43.410 --> 00:26:45.410
but the border is a bit finer.

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:47.410
That's why this TMA

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:49.410
is to be handled somewhat differently from others.

00:26:49.410 --> 00:26:54.470
Now we've talked an awful lot

00:26:54.470 --> 00:26:56.470
about restrictions,

00:26:56.470 --> 00:26:58.470
dangers, limitations.

00:26:58.470 --> 00:27:00.470
Now I'd like to talk about

00:27:00.470 --> 00:27:02.470
something very positive

00:27:02.470 --> 00:27:04.470
on the glider chart.

00:27:04.470 --> 00:27:06.470
About a relief for us

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:08.470
paraglider pilots.

00:27:08.470 --> 00:27:10.470
And those are the LS-R for Gliders.

00:27:10.470 --> 00:27:12.470
Those are the glider zones.

00:27:12.470 --> 00:27:14.470
They are marked in green.

00:27:14.470 --> 00:27:16.470
It is also LS-R,

00:27:16.470 --> 00:27:18.470
but it isn't restricted for us.

00:27:18.470 --> 00:27:20.470
It's restricted for instrument-flight aircraft

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:22.470
or instrument-flight

00:27:22.470 --> 00:27:24.470
aircraft.

00:27:24.470 --> 00:27:26.470
And it's therefore a relief for us,

00:27:26.470 --> 00:27:28.470
where we get closer to the clouds.

00:27:28.470 --> 00:27:30.470
We'll get to cloud clearances

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:32.470
shortly.

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:34.610
And what exactly that means.

00:27:34.610 --> 00:27:36.610
The LS-Rs are active from 1 March

00:27:36.610 --> 00:27:38.610
to 31 October.

00:27:38.610 --> 00:27:40.610
Here too,

00:27:40.610 --> 00:27:42.610
watch that you look at those times.

00:27:42.610 --> 00:27:44.610
And that you don't, for example,

00:27:44.610 --> 00:27:46.610
on a super good day in February —

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:48.610
that can happen —

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:50.610
go thermal flying

00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:52.610
and aren't even aware

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:54.610
whether the zone is active.

00:27:54.610 --> 00:27:56.610
So watch out

00:27:56.610 --> 00:27:58.610
that you only really start using them from 1 March.

00:27:58.610 --> 00:28:00.610
And also for the exam,

00:28:00.610 --> 00:28:02.610
for the theory exam,

00:28:02.610 --> 00:28:04.610
but also for the theory question at the practical exam,

00:28:04.610 --> 00:28:06.610
if you take your exam in winter,

00:28:06.610 --> 00:28:08.610
it can happen

00:28:08.610 --> 00:28:10.610
that the examiner asks a sneaky question

00:28:10.610 --> 00:28:12.660
about the glider zones,

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:14.960
which then happen not to be active.

00:28:14.960 --> 00:28:16.960
Visually they look like this.

00:28:16.960 --> 00:28:18.960
Outlined in green.

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:20.960
Here too we have lower and upper limits given

00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:24.770
on the glider chart.

00:28:24.770 --> 00:28:26.850
If we talk about these LS-Rs,

00:28:26.850 --> 00:28:28.850
we inevitably also come right away

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:30.850
to the topic of cloud clearances.

00:28:30.850 --> 00:28:33.600
The cloud clearances are regulated such

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:35.600
that up to 300 metres

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:37.600
above ground

00:28:37.600 --> 00:28:39.600
you don't need a cloud clearance.

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:41.600
You just have to be outside

00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:43.600
the cloud at all times and also

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:45.600
be able to make a 180° turn.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:47.600
So you can't fly head-on into a cloud

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:49.620
until you're almost inside,

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:51.620
but you must always be able to turn around.

00:28:51.620 --> 00:28:53.620
That's very important.

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:55.670
Horizontal visibility

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:57.670
must be 1.5 kilometres

00:28:57.670 --> 00:28:59.670
and you must always be able to see the ground.

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:01.670
This rule applies up to 300 metres.

00:29:01.670 --> 00:29:03.670
It's a bit special.

00:29:03.670 --> 00:29:05.670
It's not simply said

00:29:05.670 --> 00:29:07.670
that it's in airspace G,

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:09.670
but it's only half of G.

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:11.670
So it's only 300 metres

00:29:11.670 --> 00:29:13.670
and not 600 metres,

00:29:13.670 --> 00:29:15.670
where the line is drawn.

00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:17.670
You have to remember that.

00:29:17.670 --> 00:29:20.000
Everything that's above 300 metres

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
must then keep pretty large cloud clearances.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Vertically it's 300 metres

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.000
and horizontally

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
1,500 metres of distance from the clouds.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.530
In terms of visibility it's

00:29:30.530 --> 00:29:32.530
no longer just 1.5 kilometres,

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:34.530
but it then goes up here

00:29:34.530 --> 00:29:36.530
to 5 kilometres,

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:38.530
respectively 8 kilometres,

00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:40.530
as soon as we're flying above 3050.

00:29:40.530 --> 00:29:42.530
That simply has to do with the speeds

00:29:42.530 --> 00:29:44.530
of the aircraft,

00:29:44.530 --> 00:29:46.530
because higher up

00:29:46.530 --> 00:29:48.530
higher speeds are flown

00:29:48.530 --> 00:29:50.530
and of course more time is needed

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:52.530
to react and avoid.

00:29:52.530 --> 00:29:54.530
The aircraft fly into the clouds

00:29:54.530 --> 00:29:56.530
and when they come out of the clouds

00:29:56.530 --> 00:29:58.530
and we only have 500 metres of clearance

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:00.530
from those clouds,

00:30:00.530 --> 00:30:02.530
it can under certain circumstances get tight.

00:30:02.530 --> 00:30:04.530
That's why we have

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:08.600
larger cloud clearances higher up.

00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:10.600
Except in the special case

00:30:10.600 --> 00:30:12.600
of the glider zone LS-R for Gliders,

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:15.250
it looks a bit different.

00:30:15.250 --> 00:30:17.250
In these zones

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:19.250
we have, namely,

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:21.360
a minimised cloud clearance.

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:23.360
That's 50 metres vertically

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:25.360
and 100 metres horizontally.

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:27.360
On the right-hand side

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:29.360
you can again see

00:30:29.360 --> 00:30:31.360
the lower limit and the upper limit

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:33.360
of this airspace.

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:35.440
Here it's still important

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:37.680
that you don't get confused

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:39.680
or think

00:30:39.680 --> 00:30:41.680
that at 2450,

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:43.680
in a super thermal,

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:45.680
you have to stop and fly down again.

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:47.680
You are definitely allowed

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:49.680
to climb above that altitude.

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:51.680
The only thing that then changes,

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:53.680
as soon as you're above it,

00:30:53.680 --> 00:30:55.680
are the cloud clearances.

00:30:55.680 --> 00:30:57.680
If you, for example,

00:30:57.680 --> 00:30:59.680
are at 2500,

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:02.150
then the large cloud clearances apply again.

00:31:02.150 --> 00:31:04.150
That is still important to know

00:31:04.150 --> 00:31:06.150
and sometimes at the theory exam

00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:08.150
the questions are posed in such a way

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:10.150
that perhaps

00:31:10.150 --> 00:31:12.150
you trip up and think

00:31:12.150 --> 00:31:14.150
you can only fly up to 2550.

00:31:14.150 --> 00:31:16.150
But that doesn't apply to the flying,

00:31:16.150 --> 00:31:18.150
but only to the cloud clearances

00:31:18.150 --> 00:31:21.320
you have to keep.

00:31:21.320 --> 00:31:23.320
Many of these LS-Rs

00:31:23.320 --> 00:31:25.320
don't have any suffix at the back

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:27.320
and just the altitude.

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:29.460
And some have

00:31:29.460 --> 00:31:31.460
a suffix at the back

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:33.460
of MO.

00:31:33.460 --> 00:31:35.460
MO means it's only active

00:31:35.460 --> 00:31:37.600
when the military is off.

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:39.600
So when the military

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:41.600
is not active.

00:31:41.600 --> 00:31:43.600
MA is also always active,

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:45.600
when the military is not released.

00:31:45.600 --> 00:31:47.600
With MA the difference is,

00:31:47.600 --> 00:31:49.600
when the military is active there,

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:51.650
it can be

00:31:51.650 --> 00:31:53.650
that it's then immediately

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:55.650
released.

00:31:55.650 --> 00:31:57.650
If the military is active

00:31:57.650 --> 00:31:59.650
and MA is shown, you can ask.

00:31:59.650 --> 00:32:01.650
Perhaps it then opens

00:32:01.650 --> 00:32:03.650
the airspace right away,

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:05.650
because the military is perhaps

00:32:05.650 --> 00:32:07.650
at another location

00:32:07.650 --> 00:32:09.650
or isn't using the airspace.

00:32:09.650 --> 00:32:14.130
Now we've heard a whole lot of theory.

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:16.130
I hope

00:32:16.130 --> 00:32:18.130
you're still listening.

00:32:18.130 --> 00:32:20.130
Now we come to a theory question.

00:32:20.130 --> 00:32:22.130
As warm-up

00:32:22.130 --> 00:32:24.130
for the theory exam

00:32:24.130 --> 00:32:26.130
and of course also

00:32:26.130 --> 00:32:28.130
for your flying life.

00:32:28.130 --> 00:32:30.130
We're standing at the launch site

00:32:30.130 --> 00:32:32.130
and have to know

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:34.130
how high I fly,

00:32:34.130 --> 00:32:36.130
what are the cloud clearances,

00:32:36.130 --> 00:32:38.130
how far do I have to see,

00:32:38.130 --> 00:32:40.130
and am I legally underway

00:32:40.130 --> 00:32:43.240
or should I even launch at all?

00:32:43.240 --> 00:32:45.240
Dear Silo.

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:47.320
Basically I always ask myself

00:32:47.320 --> 00:32:49.320
the five questions

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:51.320
when I'm at a point.

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:53.320
On the one hand it's the season

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:55.320
because of the glider-zone period.

00:32:55.320 --> 00:32:57.320
Am I between March and October

00:32:57.320 --> 00:32:59.320
or am I in winter?

00:32:59.320 --> 00:33:01.320
That would affect me in the glider zone.

00:33:01.320 --> 00:33:03.560
The second is the day of the week

00:33:03.560 --> 00:33:05.560
and the time of day

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:07.560
because of the military,

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:09.560
to know how high I'm allowed to climb

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.700
if it's going great.

00:33:11.700 --> 00:33:13.700
Then I have to know,

00:33:13.700 --> 00:33:15.700
am I north or south

00:33:15.700 --> 00:33:18.420
of the dividing line?

00:33:18.420 --> 00:33:20.420
Am I in the Mittelland or in the Alps?

00:33:20.420 --> 00:33:22.420
The altitude I'm currently at

00:33:22.420 --> 00:33:24.420
is very important to know

00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:26.420
and so is the location.

00:33:26.420 --> 00:33:28.420
Am I within the radius

00:33:28.420 --> 00:33:30.420
of a restricted zone?

00:33:30.420 --> 00:33:32.420
That's very important.

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:34.420
If you can answer these five questions,

00:33:34.420 --> 00:33:36.420
then you also come

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:38.420
relatively quickly

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:41.010
to the solution.

00:33:41.010 --> 00:33:43.010
Maybe you can quickly press pause

00:33:43.010 --> 00:33:45.010
and not yet go on to the next slide,

00:33:45.010 --> 00:33:47.010
and think about the task.

00:33:47.010 --> 00:33:49.010
On the next slide

00:33:49.010 --> 00:33:54.740
the explanation comes right after.

00:33:54.740 --> 00:33:56.740
You can see, it's location B.

00:33:56.740 --> 00:33:58.980
It's a maximum altitude

00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:00.980
of 3,050 m,

00:34:00.980 --> 00:34:03.090
because we are north

00:34:03.090 --> 00:34:05.090
of the dividing line.

00:34:05.090 --> 00:34:07.090
It's a bit nasty here,

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:09.090
it's right at the border,

00:34:09.090 --> 00:34:11.090
but slightly above or to the left of it

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:13.090
means we're in the Mittelland.

00:34:13.090 --> 00:34:15.090
The answer with 4,550 m

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:17.090
you can actually already cross off.

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:19.090
Very often, as far as the theory exam is concerned,

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:21.090
you arrive at the correct answer

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:23.090
through the process

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:25.090
of elimination.

00:34:25.090 --> 00:34:27.240
Flying forbidden —

00:34:27.240 --> 00:34:29.240
I see no reason for that here.

00:34:29.240 --> 00:34:31.250
We don't have an airfield,

00:34:31.250 --> 00:34:33.250
no heliport nearby.

00:34:33.250 --> 00:34:35.250
Not in a Danger or Restricted Area,

00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:37.250
to be more precise.

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:39.250
It all looks like flying is fine.

00:34:39.250 --> 00:34:41.910
The altitude is

00:34:41.910 --> 00:34:43.910
the same for B and C.

00:34:43.910 --> 00:34:45.910
Now we have to figure out

00:34:45.910 --> 00:34:47.910
how it is with the cloud clearances.

00:34:47.910 --> 00:34:50.080
We're up at 2,700 m.

00:34:50.080 --> 00:34:52.080
That means

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:54.080
visibility is 5 km.

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:56.080
We see that here.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:58.080
Next to the legs it says 5 km,

00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:00.080
because we're still below the 3,050 m.

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:02.630
Higher than that we're not allowed,

00:35:02.630 --> 00:35:04.630
because we're in the Mittelland.

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:07.320
As for the cloud clearances,

00:35:07.320 --> 00:35:09.320
we have to consider

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:11.320
whether we're in a glider zone or not.

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:13.320
That's a bit mean.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:15.320
You could think

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:17.320
you're inside.

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:19.320
But if you look at the numbers

00:35:19.320 --> 00:35:21.320
for the LS-R21 carefully,

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:23.320
the LS-R for Gliders

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:25.320
only goes up to 2,450 m.

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:27.320
But we are already

00:35:27.320 --> 00:35:29.320
in the air at 2,700 m.

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:31.330
That means

00:35:31.330 --> 00:35:33.330
we are above it.

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:35.330
We may fly there.

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:37.330
It's not forbidden.

00:35:37.330 --> 00:35:39.330
But unfortunately we have to

00:35:39.330 --> 00:35:41.330
again keep the large cloud clearances,

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:43.510
so 300 m and 1.5 km.

00:35:43.510 --> 00:35:45.510
So I'm trying to send you off

00:35:45.510 --> 00:35:47.510
with the approach

00:35:47.510 --> 00:35:49.510
of proceeding

00:35:49.510 --> 00:35:51.510
by these criteria,

00:35:51.510 --> 00:35:53.510
so that you're always legally underway

00:35:53.510 --> 00:35:55.510
and can also answer questions for exams

00:35:55.510 --> 00:35:57.590
correctly.

00:35:57.590 --> 00:35:59.590
Then we have here once again

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:02.280
a small example.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:04.480
We have to go through everything.

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:06.480
Here, watch out.

00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:08.480
We see

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:11.110
we're up at 1,850 m.

00:36:11.110 --> 00:36:13.110
Airspace D goes from 1,600 m

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:15.110
up to 1,350 m.

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:17.110
So you're rather quickly tempted

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:19.110
to say it's forbidden.

00:36:19.110 --> 00:36:21.110
There I'm right in it.

00:36:21.110 --> 00:36:23.110
Flying forbidden.

00:36:23.110 --> 00:36:25.110
Either don't launch,

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:27.110
tick 'flying forbidden' at the exam

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:29.220
and move on.

00:36:29.220 --> 00:36:31.220
Think it through here again

00:36:31.220 --> 00:36:33.220
really carefully.

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:35.220
These are the special rules

00:36:35.220 --> 00:36:37.840
that work in our favour.

00:36:37.840 --> 00:36:39.840
We're here in Meiringen.

00:36:39.840 --> 00:36:41.840
It of course helps

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:43.840
if you know the chart a little.

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:45.840
But here we are south of the line.

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:48.130
You're in the Alps.

00:36:48.130 --> 00:36:50.130
That's why the special rule

00:36:50.130 --> 00:36:52.130
comes into play,

00:36:52.130 --> 00:36:54.130
that you fly through 300 m

00:36:54.130 --> 00:36:56.130
below the TMA.

00:36:56.130 --> 00:36:58.130
And we are,

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:00.130
as you can see up here,

00:37:00.130 --> 00:37:02.130
at 150 m above the ground,

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:04.280
legally underway.

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:06.770
With a maximum altitude

00:37:06.770 --> 00:37:08.770
of 300 m above the ground, of course.

00:37:08.770 --> 00:37:10.770
Here no altitude

00:37:10.770 --> 00:37:12.770
above sea level is given,

00:37:12.770 --> 00:37:14.770
because the ground varies as well.

00:37:14.770 --> 00:37:16.770
If we follow the terrain

00:37:16.770 --> 00:37:18.770
and simply always keep the 300 m,

00:37:18.770 --> 00:37:22.080
we're therefore legally underway at all times.

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:24.080
It's only 300 m,

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:26.080
so cloud clearance:

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:28.200
no cloud clearance required,

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:30.200
fly outside the clouds

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:32.210
with a 180° turn possible at any time,

00:37:32.210 --> 00:37:37.720
and ground visibility.

00:37:37.720 --> 00:37:39.720
I'd like to thank you for your attention.

00:37:39.720 --> 00:37:41.720
Thanks for listening.

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:43.720
I hope I was able to give you something to take with you,

00:37:43.720 --> 00:37:45.720
so that as a first step

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:47.830
you can approach this positively,

00:37:47.830 --> 00:37:49.830
can go in,

00:37:49.830 --> 00:37:51.830
can prepare yourselves for the exam,

00:37:51.830 --> 00:37:53.830
and then as a second step of course

00:37:53.830 --> 00:37:55.830
have lots of fun in everyday flying

00:37:55.830 --> 00:37:57.830
and that you are at all times safely

00:37:57.830 --> 00:37:59.830
and legally on your way in Swiss airspace.

00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:01.830
Many thanks.

00:38:01.830 --> 00:38:03.830
See you soon.
